          "id": "business-ethics-201-l01-c3",
          "title": "One-Tier vs. Two-Tier Boards",
          "content": "In the world of corporate governance, there are two primary types of board structures that companies can adopt: one-tier boards and two-tier boards. The one-tier model is commonly found in Anglo-American countries, such as the United States and the United Kingdom. In this structure, both executive directors, who are involved in the day-to-day operations of the company, and non-executive directors, who provide independent oversight, sit together on a single board. This arrangement can foster close collaboration and quick decision-making, as all members are working together in one group. However, it can also lead to potential conflicts of interest. For example, when the board needs to evaluate the performance of the executives who are also its members, it can create challenges in ensuring accountability and transparency.\nOn the other hand, the two-tier model is more commonly used in Continental European countries, such as Germany and the Netherlands. This structure distinctly separates the management board, which is responsible for running the company, from the supervisory board, which oversees the management's activities. This separation can enhance oversight and reduce conflicts of interest, as the supervisory board can focus solely on monitoring the management without being involved in daily operations. Additionally, Germany's two-tier model includes a unique feature known as codetermination, where employees are represented on the supervisory board. This means that workers have a formal role in governance, allowing them to voice their opinions and concerns about company decisions, which can lead to more balanced and fair corporate practices.\nContext recap: In the world of corporate governance, there are two primary types of board structures that companies can adopt: one-tier boards and two-tier boards. The one-tier model is commonly found in Anglo-American countries, such as the United States and the United Kingdom. In this structure, both executive directors, who are involved in the day-to-day operations of the company, and non-executive directors, who provide independent oversight, sit together on a single board. This arrangement can foster close collaboration and quick decision-making, as all members are working together in one group.\nWhy this matters: One-Tier vs. Two-Tier Boards helps learners in Business connect ideas from Corporate Governance & Legal Frameworks to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
