          "id": "business-ethics-201-l02-c1",
          "title": "Fiduciary Duties",
          "content": "In the world of business, directors play a crucial role in guiding a company. They have two key responsibilities known as fiduciary duties that they must uphold to ensure the company operates ethically and effectively. The first duty is called the duty of care. This means that directors need to make well-informed decisions that are in the best interest of the company. To fulfill this duty, they should act like a reasonable person would in similar situations. This involves carefully reviewing important documents, asking thoughtful questions, and seeking advice from experts when they are unsure about something. By doing this, they can make choices that are beneficial for the company and its shareholders.\nThe second duty is known as the duty of loyalty. This duty requires directors to always put the interests of the corporation ahead of their own personal interests. In other words, they should avoid any actions that could lead to a conflict of interest. For example, directors should not engage in self-dealing, which means they should not make decisions that benefit themselves at the expense of the company. They should also refrain from competing with the company or taking business opportunities that rightfully belong to the corporation. By adhering to these fiduciary duties, directors help maintain trust and integrity within the business, ensuring that the company can thrive and serve its shareholders effectively.\nContext recap: In the world of business, directors play a crucial role in guiding a company. They have two key responsibilities known as fiduciary duties that they must uphold to ensure the company operates ethically and effectively. The first duty is called the duty of care. This means that directors need to make well-informed decisions that are in the best interest of the company.\nWhy this matters: Fiduciary Duties helps learners in Business connect ideas from Corporate Governance & Legal Frameworks to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
