          "id": "business-ethics-201-l03-c1",
          "title": "The Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX)",
          "content": "The Sarbanes-Oxley Act, commonly known as SOX, was introduced in 2002 as a direct response to significant corporate scandals, particularly those involving Enron and WorldCom. These scandals highlighted the need for stronger regulations to protect investors and ensure the integrity of financial reporting. As a result, SOX brought about major changes in corporate governance practices across the United States. One of the most important aspects of this law is that it requires the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) and Chief Financial Officer (CFO) of a company to personally certify that the financial statements they provide are accurate and truthful. This means that they are held accountable for the information that is shared with investors and the public. Furthermore, the Act mandates that companies must implement and maintain robust internal controls over their financial reporting processes. This is crucial for preventing mistakes and detecting any fraudulent activities that may occur. Another significant provision is that audit committees, which are responsible for overseeing the company's financial reporting and auditing processes, must be made up entirely of independent directors. This helps to ensure that the committee can operate without any conflicts of interest. Additionally, the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) was created to regulate and oversee the auditors who review financial statements, ensuring they adhere to strict standards. Lastly, the penalties for engaging in securities fraud were significantly increased, with offenders facing prison sentences of up to 25 years. Overall, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act plays a vital role in promoting transparency and accountability in corporate America, ultimately aiming to protect investors and maintain trust in the financial markets.\nContext recap: The Sarbanes-Oxley Act, commonly known as SOX, was introduced in 2002 as a direct response to significant corporate scandals, particularly those involving Enron and WorldCom. These scandals highlighted the need for stronger regulations to protect investors and ensure the integrity of financial reporting. As a result, SOX brought about major changes in corporate governance practices across the United States. One of the most important aspects of this law is that it requires the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) and Chief Financial Officer (CFO) of a company to personally certify that the financial statements they provide are accurate and truthful.\nWhy this matters: The Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) helps learners in Business connect ideas from Corporate Governance & Legal Frameworks to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
