          "id": "business-ethics-201-l06-c3",
          "title": "Intellectual Property Basics",
          "content": "Intellectual property law plays a crucial role in protecting the rights of creators and inventors. It ensures that those who come up with new ideas, inventions, or creative works have the exclusive rights to benefit from their efforts. For instance, patents are a type of intellectual property that safeguard new inventions and processes for a duration of 20 years. To be eligible for a patent, an invention must meet specific criteria: it must be new, useful, and not obvious to others who are knowledgeable in the same field. This encourages innovation by rewarding inventors for their hard work.\nTrademarks are another important aspect of intellectual property. They protect brand identifiers, which include names, logos, and slogans that help consumers recognize and differentiate products in the marketplace. Trademarks can last indefinitely, provided they are actively used in business, which helps maintain brand identity and consumer trust.\nCopyrights protect original works of art, literature, music, and other creative expressions. The protection lasts for the life of the author plus an additional 70 years, allowing creators to benefit from their work long after it has been created.\nLastly, trade secrets, such as the closely guarded Coca-Cola formula, are protected indefinitely as long as the information remains confidential and is not disclosed to the public. Each form of intellectual property serves a distinct purpose, helping creators safeguard their work and maintain a competitive advantage in the market.\nContext recap: Intellectual property law plays a crucial role in protecting the rights of creators and inventors. It ensures that those who come up with new ideas, inventions, or creative works have the exclusive rights to benefit from their efforts. For instance, patents are a type of intellectual property that safeguard new inventions and processes for a duration of 20 years. To be eligible for a patent, an invention must meet specific criteria: it must be new, useful, and not obvious to others who are knowledgeable in the same field.\nWhy this matters: Intellectual Property Basics helps learners in Business connect ideas from Corporate Governance & Legal Frameworks to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
